"Sauer J., Domisch S., Nowak C., Haase P.","Low mountain ranges: Summit traps for montane freshwater species under climate change",2011,"Biodiversity and Conservation","20","13",,"3133","3146",,,10.1007/s10531-011-0140-y,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-81255135915&partnerID=40&md5=64644e5cf1d283dfe5780d9869fdcb76","Biodiversity and Climate Research Centre (BiK-F), Senckenberganlage 25, 60325 Frankfurt am Main, Germany; Department of Limnology and Conservation, Senckenberg Research Institutes and Natural History Museums, Clamecystrasse 12, 63571 Gelnhausen, Germany","Sauer, J., Biodiversity and Climate Research Centre (BiK-F), Senckenberganlage 25, 60325 Frankfurt am Main, Germany, Department of Limnology and Conservation, Senckenberg Research Institutes and Natural History Museums, Clamecystrasse 12, 63571 Gelnhausen, Germany; Domisch, S., Biodiversity and Climate Research Centre (BiK-F), Senckenberganlage 25, 60325 Frankfurt am Main, Germany, Department of Limnology and Conservation, Senckenberg Research Institutes and Natural History Museums, Clamecystrasse 12, 63571 Gelnhausen, Germany; Nowak, C., Biodiversity and Climate Research Centre (BiK-F), Senckenberganlage 25, 60325 Frankfurt am Main, Germany, Department of Limnology and Conservation, Senckenberg Research Institutes and Natural History Museums, Clamecystrasse 12, 63571 Gelnhausen, Germany; Haase, P., Biodiversity and Climate Research Centre (BiK-F), Senckenberganlage 25, 60325 Frankfurt am Main, Germany, Department of Limnology and Conservation, Senckenberg Research Institutes and Natural History Museums, Clamecystrasse 12, 63571 Gelnhausen, Germany","Global climate change (GCC) is expected to lead to massive loss of global biodiversity in the alpine regions of mountain ranges. Studies on the potential effects of GCC on low mountain areas remain sparse, however, despite the high conservation value of these areas as biodiversity refugia. We chose a species distribution modeling approach to assess potential GCC impacts on the future distributions of montane freshwater invertebrates under two different greenhouse gas scenarios and three averaged general circulation models. For this, ensemble models consisting of six algorithms [generalized linear model (GLM), generalized boosted model (GBM), generalized additive model (GAM), classification tree analysis (CTA), artificial neural networks (ANN), and multivariate adaptive regression splines (MARS)] were applied to project areas of 23 cold-stenothermic aquatic insects from montane regions of Central Europe. We found an average loss of 70-80% of the potential distribution for the study species until 2080, depending on the underlying Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change scenario. Species distribution ranges below 1000 m above sea level were found to decrease by up to ~96% according to the severest greenhouse gas emission scenario. While the Alps remain the single main refugium under the A2a greenhouse gas emission scenario, the more moderate climate scenario B2a shows fragmented potential persistence of montane insects in some low mountain ranges. The results show that montane freshwater assemblages in low mountain ranges are particularly threatened by ongoing GCC. As vertical dispersal is limited by elevational restriction, low mountain ranges may act as summit traps under GCC. We thus propose that GCC will lead to the extinction of several species and unique genetic lineages of postglacial relict species, resulting in a significant decline in Central European fauna. © 2011 Springer Science+Business Media B.V.","BIOMOD; Climate change; Low mountain ranges; Montane aquatic insects; Species distribution models","artificial neural network; biodiversity; climate change; freshwater ecosystem; global change; greenhouse gas; habitat conservation; habitat loss; Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change; invertebrate; montane forest; mountain region; multivariate analysis; refugium; Alps; Central Europe; Hexapoda; Invertebrata",,,,,,"Akaike, H., Information theory and an extension of the maximum likelihood principle (1973) Proceedings of the Second International Symposium On Information Theory, Budapest, pp. 267-281. , Petrov BN, Csaki F (eds); Araújo, M.B., Guisan, A., Five (or so) challenges for species distribution modelling (2006) J Biogeogr, 33, pp. 1677-1688; Araujo, M.B., Whittaker, R.J., Ladle, R.J., Reducing uncertainty in projections of extinction risk from climate change (2005) Global Ecol Biogeogr, 14, pp. 529-538; Asch, K., The 1: 5 Million International Geological Map of Europe and Adjacent Areas (2005) Bundesanstalt Für Geowissenschaften Und Rohstoffe (BGR), , Hannover; Bässler, C., Müller, J., Hothorn, T., Estimation of the extinction risk for high-montane species as a consequence of global warming and assessment of their suitability as cross-taxon indicators (2010) Ecol Indi, 10, pp. 341-352; Beniston, M., Mountain weather and climate: A general overview and a focus on climatic change in the Alps (2006) Ecology of High Altitude Aquatic Systems In the Alps, Hydrobiol, 562, pp. 3-16. , In: Lami A, Boggero A (eds); Braukmann, U., Zoozönologische und saprobiologische Beiträge zu einer allgemeinen regionalen Bachtypologie (1987) Fundam Appl Limnol Arch Hydrobiol, 26, pp. 1-355; Collier, K.J., Smith, B.J., Dispersal of adult caddisflies (Trichoptera) into forests alongside three New Zealand streams (1997) Hydrobiologica, 361, pp. 51-65; (2010) Centre Suisse De Cartographie De La Faune, , CSF, Data accessed February 2010; Diaz, H.F., Grosjean, M., Graumlich, L., Climate variability and change in high elevation regions: past, present and future (2003) Climatic Change, 59, pp. 1-4; Dirnböck, T., Essl, F., Rabitsch, W., Disproportional risk for habitat loss of high-altitude endemic species under climate change (2011) Glob Chang Biol, 17, pp. 990-996; Domisch, S., Jähnig, S.C., Haase, P., Climate-change winners and losers: Stream macroinvertebrates of a submontan